records.subject: MAE
records.description: Presents current research by university faculty, visiting speakers and graduate students. Required of all full-time MAE graduate students.

records.title: Weather Briefing
records.subject: MET
records.description: Stimulates discussion about recent, current and future weather using various data sources, including satellites, surface observations, radar, model and upper air data. Underscores the importance of the human element in weather forecasting. Students must attend the weekly weather briefing and participate in a national weather forecasting contest. Content varies and course may be repeated for a maximum of three credits.
records.description_with_prereqs: Stimulates discussion about recent, current and future weather using various data sources, including satellites, surface observations, radar, model and upper air data. Underscores the importance of the human element in weather forecasting. Students must attend the weekly weather briefing and participate in a national weather forecasting contest. Content varies and course may be repeated for a maximum of three credits.

records.title: Synoptic Meteorology 2
records.subject: MET
records.description: Basic analysis techniques, scalar and vector fields, thermodynamic diagrams, synoptic calculations, 4-dimensional atmospheric structure, weather map discussions.
records.description_with_prereqs: Basic analysis techniques, scalar and vector fields, thermodynamic diagrams, synoptic calculations, 4-dimensional atmospheric structure, weather map discussions. (Prerequisites: MET 3401)

records.title: Data Anlys in Meteorology
records.subject: MET
records.description: Covers different types of multidimensional large datasets (i.e., big data) from a variety of sources used to describe physical and dynamical processes of the weather and climate system. Emphasizes understanding and interpreting the data through basic programming, plotting and analysis. Lab requires use of various data and formats. (Q)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers different types of multidimensional large datasets (i.e., big data) from a variety of sources used to describe physical and dynamical processes of the weather and climate system. Emphasizes understanding and interpreting the data through basic programming, plotting and analysis. Lab requires use of various data and formats. (Q) (Prerequisites: CSE 1100, CSE 1502, CSE 1503)

records.title: Atmospheric Dynamics 2
records.subject: MET
records.description: Studies circulation and vorticity, scale analysis, friction and turbulence, sound, gravity and Rossby waves, instability, numerical weather prediction.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies circulation and vorticity, scale analysis, friction and turbulence, sound, gravity and Rossby waves, instability, numerical weather prediction. (Prerequisites: MET 4305)

records.title: Climatology
records.subject: MET
records.description: Studies the distribution of weather elements globally, continental positioning, rain shields, hydrological cycle, meteorological databases, El Nino impacts on humans, global warming and the anthropogenic greenhouse effect.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the distribution of weather elements globally, continental positioning, rain shields, hydrological cycle, meteorological databases, El Nino impacts on humans, global warming and the anthropogenic greenhouse effect. (Prerequisites: MTH 2401, OCN 2407)

records.title: Mesoscale Meteorology
records.subject: MET
records.description: Surveys conceptual models and analyzes techniques for mesoscale phenomena. Includes mesoscale convective complexes, severe storms, atmospheric instability, mesoscale gravity waves, squall lines, drylines, topographic effects, mesoscale clouds and precipitation processes, coastal showers, the sea breeze and other local phenomena.
records.description_with_prereqs: Surveys conceptual models and analyzes techniques for mesoscale phenomena. Includes mesoscale convective complexes, severe storms, atmospheric instability, mesoscale gravity waves, squall lines, drylines, topographic effects, mesoscale clouds and precipitation processes, coastal showers, the sea breeze and other local phenomena. (Prerequisites: OCN 2407)

records.title: Dynamic Meterology 2
records.subject: MET
records.description: Dynamics of the atmosphere including theorems on circulation and vorticity; scale analysis; friction and turbulence; sound, gravity and Rossby waves; instability; numerical weather prediction.
records.description_with_prereqs: Dynamics of the atmosphere including theorems on circulation and vorticity; scale analysis; friction and turbulence; sound, gravity and Rossby waves; instability; numerical weather prediction. (Prerequisites: MET 5305)

records.title: Global Climate Change
records.subject: MET
records.description: Reviews the present state of climate change science. Addresses proxy reconstruction, uncertainty (feedbacks) and sensitivity, climate modeling, changing sea level and radiative forcing (natural and anthropogenic). Combines background material with relevant peer-reviewed literature. Includes research in an area of interest to the student.
records.description_with_prereqs: Reviews the present state of climate change science. Addresses proxy reconstruction, uncertainty (feedbacks) and sensitivity, climate modeling, changing sea level and radiative forcing (natural and anthropogenic). Combines background material with relevant peer-reviewed literature. Includes research in an area of interest to the student.

records.title: Financial Accounting
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Studies accounting concepts, the accounting model, measurement processes, financial statements, financial analysis, the accounting cycle, monetary and fixed assets, inventory, current and long-term liabilities, and equity structures of partnerships, proprietorships and corporations.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies accounting concepts, the accounting model, measurement processes, financial statements, financial analysis, the accounting cycle, monetary and fixed assets, inventory, current and long-term liabilities, and equity structures of partnerships, proprietorships and corporations.

records.title: Public Finance
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Covers concepts and methods of financial management in federal, state and local governments including the analysis of the theory and practice of public finance through taxation, debt instruments, intergovernmental funds and other revenue sources. Reviews financial planning, forecasting, budgeting and financial management practices.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers concepts and methods of financial management in federal, state and local governments including the analysis of the theory and practice of public finance through taxation, debt instruments, intergovernmental funds and other revenue sources. Reviews financial planning, forecasting, budgeting and financial management practices. (Prerequisites: MGT 5000)

records.title: Mgmt Theory & Thought
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Overviews classical and contemporary management philosophies and theories. Focuses on managing enterprises in a rapidly changing global economy. Includes developing strategic vision, planning, organizing, directing and controlling, social responsibility and international management.
records.description_with_prereqs: Overviews classical and contemporary management philosophies and theories. Focuses on managing enterprises in a rapidly changing global economy. Includes developing strategic vision, planning, organizing, directing and controlling, social responsibility and international management.

records.title: Applied Mgmt Project
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Covers concepts, tools and techniques for evaluation of research proposals and studies. Involves designing, conducting, evaluating and presenting oral and written forms of research. Assignments build on quantitative and qualitative research methods. Recommended for the graduating semester. May serve as the capstone for certain majors.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers concepts, tools and techniques for evaluation of research proposals and studies. Involves designing, conducting, evaluating and presenting oral and written forms of research. Assignments build on quantitative and qualitative research methods. Recommended for the graduating semester. May serve as the capstone for certain majors.

records.title: Leadership Thry & Eff Mgt
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Introduces and examines historical development of leadership theory and supporting research. Considers past and contemporary theory in self-analysis by students to define their own leadership styles.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces and examines historical development of leadership theory and supporting research. Considers past and contemporary theory in self-analysis by students to define their own leadership styles. (Prerequisites: MGT 5013)

records.title: Computer Systems Admin
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Covers a chief information officer's multiple roles in management of computer-based resources, both centralized and networked data center operations with wide-area networks and local-area networks; computer-based systems development/maintenance/security. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or equivalent.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers a chief information officer's multiple roles in management of computer-based resources, both centralized and networked data center operations with wide-area networks and local-area networks; computer-based systems development/maintenance/security. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or equivalent.) (Prerequisites: MGT 5014)

records.title: Telcom Systems Mgmt
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Explores the legal and technical operation environment of telecommunications in organizations. Assesses organizational ramifications of government telecommunications laws, policies and deregulatory activities. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or equivalent.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Explores the legal and technical operation environment of telecommunications in organizations. Assesses organizational ramifications of government telecommunications laws, policies and deregulatory activities. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or equivalent.) (Prerequisites: MGT 5014)

records.title: Adv Mgmt Info Systems
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Covers the relationship between information technology and the strategic operational and functional areas of organizations in both global and domestic environments. May serve as the capstone for certain majors.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the relationship between information technology and the strategic operational and functional areas of organizations in both global and domestic environments. May serve as the capstone for certain majors. (Prerequisites: MGT 5014)

records.title: Hum Res in Business
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Examines all aspects of human resources management in global business enterprises. Requires extensive, academic-style writing and case study analysis.
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines all aspects of human resources management in global business enterprises. Requires extensive, academic-style writing and case study analysis.

records.subject: MGT
records.description: Examines innovation and entrepreneurship in modern society. Requires extensive, academic-style writing and case study analysis.
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines innovation and entrepreneurship in modern society. Requires extensive, academic-style writing and case study analysis.

records.title: Research Methods 2
records.subject: MGT
records.description: Explores qualitative research methods. Involves extensive writing and exploration of quantitative research methods in preparation for the dissertation proposal. Reviews chapters of individual dissertations and sample dissertation topics emphasizing quantitative methods. May be repeated for credit. (Requirement: Successful completion of doctoral comprehensive examination.)

records.title: Military Science 1
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Studies the history, mission and organization of Army ROTC and the U.S. Army; customs, courtesies, squad organization and first aid; and leadership development through practical exercises. Academic classes meet one hour weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and field exercises.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the history, mission and organization of Army ROTC and the U.S. Army; customs, courtesies, squad organization and first aid; and leadership development through practical exercises. Academic classes meet one hour weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and field exercises. (Prerequisites: MSC 1001)

records.title: Leadership Laboratory II
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Students engage in a minimum of 4.5 hours of basic military leadership and management techniques to include physical training, troop leading procedures, field training and individual and small unit tactics and training.
records.description_with_prereqs: Students engage in a minimum of 4.5 hours of basic military leadership and management techniques to include physical training, troop leading procedures, field training and individual and small unit tactics and training. (Prerequisites: MSC 1003)

records.title: Military Science 2
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Land navigation and map reading; basic leadership and continued leadership development through practical exercises; Army communications procedures. Academic classes meet two hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and additional weekend field exercises.
records.description_with_prereqs: Land navigation and map reading; basic leadership and continued leadership development through practical exercises; Army communications procedures. Academic classes meet two hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and additional weekend field exercises. (Prerequisites: MSC 2001)

records.title: Military Science 2
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Land navigation and map reading; basic leadership and continued leadership development through practical exercises; Army communications procedures. Academic classes meet two hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and additional weekend field exercises.
records.description_with_prereqs: Land navigation and map reading; basic leadership and continued leadership development through practical exercises; Army communications procedures. Academic classes meet two hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club, Color Guard, Drill Team and additional weekend field exercises. (Prerequisites: MSC 2001)

records.title: Military Science 3
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Military estimates, operation orders and platoon tactics; weapons, land navigation, military skills and communications II; instructional techniques; and development of leadership through tactical exercises. Classes meet three hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club and additional weekend field exercises (attendance required).
records.description_with_prereqs: Military estimates, operation orders and platoon tactics; weapons, land navigation, military skills and communications II; instructional techniques; and development of leadership through tactical exercises. Classes meet three hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Optional: Ranger Company, Cadet Club and additional weekend field exercises (attendance required). (Prerequisites: MSC 3001)

records.title: Military Science 4
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Military correspondence, staff functions and logistics; military history; military personnel management, military justice and advanced ethics; and continued leadership development through practical exercises. Classes meet three hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Field exercises (attendance is required). Optional: Ranger Company and Cadet Club.
records.description_with_prereqs: Military correspondence, staff functions and logistics; military history; military personnel management, military justice and advanced ethics; and continued leadership development through practical exercises. Classes meet three hours weekly. Leadership lab meets 1.5 hours weekly. Field exercises (attendance is required). Optional: Ranger Company and Cadet Club. (Prerequisites: MSC 4001)

records.title: Independ Study in Mil Sci
records.subject: MSC
records.description: Provides a detailed systems approach to the study and understanding of military science, including the function of military organizations, command structures and military decision-making, and characteristics, attributes and new telecommunications technologies and components that shape innovation and technological advancement in the military. (Requirement: Department head approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides a detailed systems approach to the study and understanding of military science, including the function of military organizations, command structures and military decision-making, and characteristics, attributes and new telecommunications technologies and components that shape innovation and technological advancement in the military. (Requirement: Department head approval.) (Prerequisites: MSC 4002)

records.title: Intermediate Algebra
records.subject: MTH
records.description: Basic operations on real numbers, algebraic expressions, linear equations, inequalities, exponents, polynomials, factoring, rational functions, roots, radicals, quadratic equations and quadratic functions. Credit cannot be applied toward any Florida Tech degree.
records.description_with_prereqs: Basic operations on real numbers, algebraic expressions, linear equations, inequalities, exponents, polynomials, factoring, rational functions, roots, radicals, quadratic equations and quadratic functions. Credit cannot be applied toward any Florida Tech degree.

records.title: Precalculus
records.subject: MTH
records.description: Algebra and trigonometry that are used to develop the skills needed in calculus. Required for students who have minimal algebra and/or trigonometry preparation, or whose placement test indicated such a need. (Requirement: Passing score on placement exam or prerequisite course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Algebra and trigonometry that are used to develop the skills needed in calculus. Required for students who have minimal algebra and/or trigonometry preparation, or whose placement test indicated such a need. (Requirement: Passing score on placement exam or prerequisite course.) (Prerequisites: MTH 0111)

records.description: Algebra and trigonometry that are used to develop the skills needed in calculus. Required for students who have minimal algebra and/or trigonometry preparation, or whose placement test indicated such a need. (Requirement: Passing score on placement exam or prerequisite course.)

records.title: Calculus 1
records.subject: MTH
records.description: Functions and graphs, limits and continuity, derivatives of algebraic and trigonometric functions, chain rule; applications to maxima and minima, and to related rates. Exponential logarithmic, circular and hyperbolic functions: their inverses, derivatives and integrals. (Requirement: High school algebra and trigonometry, and a passing score on the placement test, or prerequisite course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Functions and graphs, limits and continuity, derivatives of algebraic and trigonometric functions, chain rule; applications to maxima and minima, and to related rates. Exponential logarithmic, circular and hyperbolic functions: their inverses, derivatives and integrals. records.title: Intro Parallel Process

(Requirement: Programming ability in Fortran or C.)

records.title: Group Beginning Guitar
records.subject: MUS
records.description: Introduces fundamentals of acoustic guitar playing in a participatory setting. Teaches basic open chords (major, minor, dominant seventh), common progressions and fundamental rhythmic values. Includes barre chords, basic picking patterns and single-note melodies on the sixth, fifth and fourth strings. Requires own guitar, but not prior experience. (LA)

records.description: Provides more advanced skills and instruction beyond MUS 1201. Reviews beginning guitar topics and continues with more advanced picking patterns, barre chords and scales. records.title: Intro to Ocean Engr
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Applications of engineering methods to ocean engineering design case studies and problem solving, which involve the computer as an aid. Includes individual and team approaches and student presentations of case studies.
records.description_with_prereqs: Applications of engineering methods to ocean engineering design case studies and problem solving, which involve the computer as an aid. Includes individual and team approaches and student presentations of case studies.

records.title: Engineering Materials
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Introduces engineering materials. Studies atomic structures, controlling microstructure and mechanical properties of materials such as ferrous and nonferrous alloys, polymers, composites, concrete, wood and asphalt.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces engineering materials. Studies atomic structures, controlling microstructure and mechanical properties of materials such as ferrous and nonferrous alloys, polymers, composites, concrete, wood and asphalt.

records.title: Engineering Materials Lab
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Measurement techniques, materials testing and engineering applications.
records.description_with_prereqs: Measurement techniques, materials testing and engineering applications. (Prerequisites: PHY 2091)

records.description: Measurement techniques, materials testing and engineering applications.

records.title: Hydromechanics/Wave Theory
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Introduces hydromechanics and linear wave theory. Includes derivation of basic equations for time-dependent flows, development and solutions of the linear boundary value problems for water waves and engineering application results.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces hydromechanics and linear wave theory. Includes derivation of basic equations for time-dependent flows, development and solutions of the linear boundary value problems for water waves and engineering application results. (Prerequisites: OCE 3030, OCN 3430)

records.title: Water Wave Laboratory
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Students make measurements of fluid kinematic and dynamic properties of water waves and compare results to linear wave theory. Includes experiments conducted in lab wave channels and the local coastal ocean.
records.description_with_prereqs: Students make measurements of fluid kinematic and dynamic properties of water waves and compare results to linear wave theory. Includes experiments conducted in lab wave channels and the local coastal ocean.

records.subject: OCE

records.subject: OCE
records.description: Students make measurements of fluid kinematic and dynamic properties of water waves and compare results to linear wave theory. Includes experiments conducted in lab wave channels and the local coastal ocean.

records.title: Coast Proc & Shore Des
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Introduces engineering design in the dynamic coastal zone. Focuses on shoreline design and management, the physical processes of sandy beaches, coastal sediments, surf zone dynamics, beach profiles, cross-shore and alongshore sand transport, reaction of beaches to storms, coastal structures and sea-level rise.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces engineering design in the dynamic coastal zone. Focuses on shoreline design and management, the physical processes of sandy beaches, coastal sediments, surf zone dynamics, beach profiles, cross-shore and alongshore sand transport, reaction of beaches to storms, coastal structures and sea-level rise. (Prerequisites: OCE 3521)

records.title: Ocean Engr Design
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Studies the engineering design of equipment to be used in the ocean. Uses a project approach covering the integration of weight and buoyancy calculations; corrosion, fouling and selection of materials; pressure hull design; and life support and power for an ocean system. (Requirement: Junior standing.) (Q)
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the engineering design of equipment to be used in the ocean. Uses a project approach covering the integration of weight and buoyancy calculations; corrosion, fouling and selection of materials; pressure hull design; and life support and power for an ocean system. (Requirement: Junior standing.) (Q)

records.title: Ocean Engr System Design
records.subject: OCE
records.description: The engineering fundamentals that are applied to the design of ocean-related systems, including a study of the design process and related topics, such as optimization techniques, reliability predictions and simulation techniques.
records.description_with_prereqs: The engineering fundamentals that are applied to the design of ocean-related systems, including a study of the design process and related topics, such as optimization techniques, reliability predictions and simulation techniques. (Prerequisites: OCE 3521, OCE 4541, OCE 4571)

records.title: Fund of Offshore Engr
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Includes fixed and floating structures and their interactions with the ocean environment, buoy systems and their dynamics, cables and mooring systems, dynamic positioning and model testing of offshore structures.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes fixed and floating structures and their interactions with the ocean environment, buoy systems and their dynamics, cables and mooring systems, dynamic positioning and model testing of offshore structures. (Prerequisites: MAE 3083, OCE 3030)

records.title: Fund of Naval Architecture
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Covers the theory of ship calculations. Includes loading and hydrostatic analysis, inclining experiment, subdivision and damaged stability.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the theory of ship calculations. Includes loading and hydrostatic analysis, inclining experiment, subdivision and damaged stability. (Prerequisites: MAE 3083, MTH 2201)

records.title: Des of Mar Vehicles
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Provides a working knowledge of ship hull girder, longitudinal bending in still water and waves, and simple bending theory as it applies to ship structure. Culminates in the design of a mid-ship section to classification society rules. Covers concepts that predict bending moment in irregular waves and analyzes local and transverse strength.
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides a working knowledge of ship hull girder, longitudinal bending in still water and waves, and simple bending theory as it applies to ship structure. Culminates in the design of a mid-ship section to classification society rules. Covers concepts that predict bending moment in irregular waves and analyzes local and transverse strength. (Prerequisites: OCE 4571)

records.title: Coastal Processes & Engr
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Includes an analysis of coastal processes (waves, tides, currents, wind and nearshore circulation) and resulting sedimentary deposits in the beach, inlet and nearshore wave-shelf environment as related to coastal engineering problems. Students study shorefront structures and system, as well as dredging technology.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes an analysis of coastal processes (waves, tides, currents, wind and nearshore circulation) and resulting sedimentary deposits in the beach, inlet and nearshore wave-shelf environment as related to coastal engineering problems. Students study shorefront structures and system, as well as dredging technology.

records.title: Ocean Engineering Systems
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Designed to systematically find an optimum solution for ocean-related engineering problems. Discusses of a system, man-ocean systems and systems engineering. Basic techniques of systems engineering. Requires student to do a case study of an ocean engineering system. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Designed to systematically find an optimum solution for ocean-related engineering problems. Discusses of a system, man-ocean systems and systems engineering. Basic techniques of systems engineering. Requires student to do a case study of an ocean engineering system. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)

records.title: Naval Architecture
records.subject: OCE
records.description: The theory of naval architecture, elements of ship design; ship lines, hydrostatic analysis, intact and damaged stability, strength, dimensional analysis, ABS rules, propulsion, steering, ship and platform motion, resistance, model testing; and design project. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: The theory of naval architecture, elements of ship design; ship lines, hydrostatic analysis, intact and damaged stability, strength, dimensional analysis, ABS rules, propulsion, steering, ship and platform motion, resistance, model testing; and design project. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)

records.title: Dynamics of Marine Veh
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Studies regular and irregular wave data as applied in ship dynamics. Includes uncoupled heaving, pitching and rolling motion equations; calculation of the added mass and damping coefficients; strip method; coupled motions; nonlinear roll motion; dynamic effects related to motions; and wave loads.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies regular and irregular wave data as applied in ship dynamics. Includes uncoupled heaving, pitching and rolling motion equations; calculation of the added mass and damping coefficients; strip method; coupled motions; nonlinear roll motion; dynamic effects related to motions; and wave loads. (Prerequisites: MAE 3083, MTH 2201, OCE 3030)

records.title: Appld Marine Hydrodynamics
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Provides a background for the calculation of hydrodynamic forces, forces due to waves in inviscid fluid, effect of viscosity, hydrodynamic modeling, wave drift forces and forces due to current on moored and dynamically positioned floating structures, hydrodynamic impact and its prediction, flow-induced vibration.
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides a background for the calculation of hydrodynamic forces, forces due to waves in inviscid fluid, effect of viscosity, hydrodynamic modeling, wave drift forces and forces due to current on moored and dynamically positioned floating structures, hydrodynamic impact and its prediction, flow-induced vibration. (Prerequisites: OCE 3030)

records.title: Ocean Engr Data Analysis
records.subject: OCE
records.description: Ocean monitoring requires measurement, analysis and description of processes in random seas. Students produce, from measurements, the statistical distributions of waves, parametric and spectral sea-state descriptions, directional wave spectra, ocean engineering design criteria and linear responses of ocean structures and systems. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Ocean monitoring requires measurement, analysis and description of processes in random seas. Students produce, from measurements, the statistical distributions of waves, parametric and spectral sea-state descriptions, directional wave spectra, ocean engineering design criteria and linear responses of ocean structures and systems. (Requirement: Instructor approval.)

records.title: Oceanography
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Surveys oceanography including biological, chemical, geological and physical processes in the ocean. Includes field trips.
records.description_with_prereqs: Surveys oceanography including biological, chemical, geological and physical processes in the ocean. Includes field trips.

records.title: Oceanography
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Surveys oceanography including biological, chemical, geological and physical processes in the ocean. Includes field trips.
records.description_with_prereqs: Surveys oceanography including biological, chemical, geological and physical processes in the ocean. Includes field trips.

records.title: Meteorology
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Introduces meteorological phenomena and principles, including descriptive weather elements, general atmospheric circulation, air-sea interaction and the physical mechanisms that create atmospheric motions, mixing and transfer of momentum, mass and heat.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces meteorological phenomena and principles, including descriptive weather elements, general atmospheric circulation, air-sea interaction and the physical mechanisms that create atmospheric motions, mixing and transfer of momentum, mass and heat. (Prerequisites: MTH 1001, MTH 1010)

records.title: Research Vessel Ops
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Covers nautical skills needed for scientists and engineers working on research vessels. Includes classes of ships, marine terminology, deck machinery, ship handling, seamanship. admiralty law, charts, compasses, position fixing, first aid and safety of life at sea. Also includes cruise planning cost estimation and elements of navigation.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers nautical skills needed for scientists and engineers working on research vessels. Includes classes of ships, marine terminology, deck machinery, ship handling, seamanship. admiralty law, charts, compasses, position fixing, first aid and safety of life at sea. Also includes cruise planning cost estimation and elements of navigation. (Prerequisites: ENS 1001, OCN 1010)

records.title: Biological Oceanography
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Includes relationships of biological, chemical, geological and physical aspects of the oceans to biological oceanography. Instructor advisement suggested; OCN 3111 lab may not be required as corequisite.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes relationships of biological, chemical, geological and physical aspects of the oceans to biological oceanography. Instructor advisement suggested; OCN 3111 lab may not be required as corequisite. (Prerequisites: BIO 1010, BIO 1020, CHM 1102, PHY 2002)

records.title: Bio Oceanography Lab
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Students receive field and lab experience in the use of equipment and methods in biological oceanography studies.
records.description_with_prereqs: Students receive field and lab experience in the use of equipment and methods in biological oceanography studies.

records.title: Geological Oceanography
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Introduces geological oceanography; origin and evolution of ocean basins. Includes a survey of major neritic and oceanic sediment patterns and the processes that control their distribution over time and space; and paleoceanography.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces geological oceanography; origin and evolution of ocean basins. Includes a survey of major neritic and oceanic sediment patterns and the processes that control their distribution over time and space; and paleoceanography. (Prerequisites: OCN 1010, OCN 2602)

records.title: Geo Oceanography Lab
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Field and lab exercises provide experience in the use of equipment and methods relevant to geologic investigations of the ocean.
records.description_with_prereqs: Field and lab exercises provide experience in the use of equipment and methods relevant to geologic investigations of the ocean.

records.title: Mar. Field Proj: Proposal
records.subject: OCN
records.description: Preparations are made for the summer research program (Marine Field Projects). Students are guided through the process of selecting, designing and proposing research projects to be carried out during the summer marine field project. (Requirement: Junior standing in oceanography.) (Q)
records.description_with_prereqs: Preparations are made for the summer research program (Marine Field Projects). (Requirement: Junior standing in oceanography.) (Q)

records.title: Marine & Environ Pollution
records.subject: OCN
records.description: A holistic approach to the study of pollution. Defines and discusses pollutants, quantities, sources and their impacts. Considers past and present waste disposal techniques and proposed alternatives. (Requirement: Instructor approval or prerequisite course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: A holistic approach to the study of pollution. Defines and discusses pollutants, quantities, sources and their impacts. Considers past and present waste disposal techniques and proposed alternatives. (Requirement: Instructor approval or prerequisite course.) (Prerequisites: CHM 1102, OCN 1010, OCN 3201)

records.title: Marine Pollution

records.description: An applied treatment of modeling, analysis and solution of probabilistic operations research problems. Topics chosen from decision analysis, game theory, inventory models, Markov chains, queuing theory, simulation, forecasting models. (Requirement: At least one upper-level undergraduate math course, preferably probability and statistics.)
records.description_with_prereqs: An applied treatment of modeling, analysis and solution of probabilistic operations research problems. Topics chosen from decision analysis, game theory, inventory models, Markov chains, queuing theory, simulation, forecasting models. (Requirement: At least one upper-level undergraduate math course, preferably probability and statistics.)

records.title: Mathematical Programming
records.subject: ORP
records.description: Surveys popular optimization techniques. Topics chosen from linear, integer, nonlinear, dynamic and network flow programming; combinatorial graph algorithms. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or instructor approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Surveys popular optimization techniques. Topics chosen from linear, integer, nonlinear, dynamic and network flow programming; combinatorial graph algorithms. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or instructor approval.) (Prerequisites: MTH 5102, ORP 5001)

records.title: Quality Assurance
records.subject: ORP
records.description: Covers the principles and application of statistical quality control and statistical process control. (Requirement: Undergraduate statistics course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the principles and application of statistical quality control and statistical process control. (Requirement: Undergraduate statistics course.)

records.title: Discrete Sys Simulation
records.subject: ORP
records.description: Covers the principles of building and using a discrete event simulation; construction and statistical testing of random variate generators; statistical analysis and validation of results; design of simulation projects; and variance reduction methods. (Requirement: Instructor approval or prerequisite course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the principles of building and using a discrete event simulation; construction and statistical testing of random variate generators; statistical analysis and validation of results; design of simulation projects; and variance reduction methods. (Requirement: Instructor approval or prerequisite course.) (Prerequisites: MTH 5411)

records.title: Intro to Karate

Should be taken during semester covering end of season.

records.title: Modern Physics
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Includes quantum mechanics of atoms, molecules, nuclei, solids and fundamental particles. Planck and de Broglie's laws, the Bohr model of hydrogen, elementary examples of Schroedinger's equation, relativity, elementary particles and symmetry, quantum electrodynamics and chromodynamics.

(Prerequisites: MTH 2001, MTH 2201, PHY 2002)

records.title: Quantum Mechanics
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Schrodinger equation, the uncertainty principle, one-dimensional potentials, harmonic oscillator, operator methods, tunneling, angular momentum and spin. Discusses three-dimensional problems, such as one-electron atom and N-particle systems. Introduces approximation techniques, including perturbation theory.
records.description_with_prereqs: Schrodinger equation, the uncertainty principle, one-dimensional potentials, harmonic oscillator, operator methods, tunneling, angular momentum and spin. Discusses three-dimensional problems, such as one-electron atom and N-particle systems. Introduces approximation techniques, including perturbation theory. (Prerequisites: MTH 2201, PHY 2003)

records.description: Includes modern electronic measurement and data collection methods, circuit analysis, integrated and digital circuits, noise reduction techniques, signal conditioning in experimental physics and computer interfacing. Includes a laboratory section considering the design, construction and testing of analog and digital circuits.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes modern electronic measurement and data collection methods, circuit analysis, integrated and digital circuits, noise reduction techniques, signal conditioning in experimental physics and computer interfacing. Includes a laboratory section considering the design, construction and testing of analog and digital circuits. (Prerequisites: PHY 2002)

records.title: Electromag Theory
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Includes geometry of static electric and magnetic fields, electric charges and currents, calculating electric and magnetic fields from potentials, static electric and magnetic fields inside matter, Faraday's Law of Induction and Maxwell's Equations, and propagation and radiation of electromagnetic waves.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes geometry of static electric and magnetic fields, electric charges and currents, calculating electric and magnetic fields from potentials, static electric and magnetic fields inside matter, Faraday's Law of Induction and Maxwell's Equations, and propagation and radiation of electromagnetic waves. (Prerequisites: MTH 2001, PHY 2002)

records.title: Subatomic Physics
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Introduces elementary particles, fundamental forces, nuclear structure and reactions. Includes classification and properties of particles (the Standard Model) and nuclei, particle interactions, nuclear models, nuclear decays, radiation and particle detection.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces elementary particles, fundamental forces, nuclear structure and reactions. Includes classification and properties of particles (the Standard Model) and nuclei, particle interactions, nuclear models, nuclear decays, radiation and particle detection. (Prerequisites: PHY 3035)

records.title: Electromagnetic Theory 2
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Continues PHY 5017. Includes radiating systems, multipole fields and radiation, scattering and diffraction, special theory of relativity, dynamics of relativistic particles and electromagnetic fields, scattering of charged particles, Cherenkov radiation, radiation by moving charges, Bremsstrahlung and radiation damping.
records.description_with_prereqs: Continues PHY 5017. Includes radiating systems, multipole fields and radiation, scattering and diffraction, special theory of relativity, dynamics of relativistic particles and electromagnetic fields, scattering of charged particles, Cherenkov radiation, radiation by moving charges, Bremsstrahlung and radiation damping. (Prerequisites: PHY 5017)

records.title: Thermo/Stat Physics
records.subject: PHY
records.description: Covers the principles and applications of statistical thermodynamics, thermal and general interactions of macroscopic systems and parameter measurement. Also includes basic methods and applications of statistical mechanics, equilibrium conditions, quantum statistics of ideal gases, and the kinetic theory of transport and irreversible processes. (Requirement: Background knowledge equivalent to PHY 3060.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the principles and applications of statistical thermodynamics, thermal and general interactions of macroscopic systems and parameter measurement. Also includes basic methods and applications of statistical mechanics, equilibrium conditions, quantum statistics of ideal gases, and the kinetic theory of transport and irreversible processes. (Requirement: Background knowledge equivalent to PHY 3060.)

records.title: Spec Topics-Forensic Psy
records.subject: PSF
records.description: Offers topics of particular general interest in forensic psychology, criminal justice or criminology when student interest and staffing permit. May be repeated for a maximum of four credits.
records.description_with_prereqs: Offers topics of particular general interest in forensic psychology, criminal justice or criminology when student interest and staffing permit. May be repeated for a maximum of four credits. (Prerequisites: PSF 2551)

records.title: Theories of Crime
records.subject: PSF
records.description: Explores the basic questions concerning human nature, human behavior, crime and criminality from the perspectives of sociological, psychological and criminological theories. (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Explores the basic questions concerning human nature, human behavior, crime and criminality from the perspectives of sociological, psychological and criminological theories. (SS) (Prerequisites: PSF 2551, PSY 3100)

records.title: Theories of Crime
records.subject: PSF
records.description: Explores the basic questions concerning human nature, human behavior, crime and criminality from the perspectives of sociological, psychological and criminological theories. (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Explores the basic questions concerning human nature, human behavior, crime and criminality from the perspectives of sociological, psychological and criminological theories. (SS) (Prerequisites: PSF 2551, PSY 3100)

records.title: Legal Psychology
records.subject: PSF
records.description: Examines the intersection of law and psychology as an area of research and study. Covers topics such as Supreme Court decisions, arrest and trial, juror decision-making, and relevant problems or concerns that arise during investigation, trial and sentencing. (Requirements: Junior standing and prerequisite course or instructor approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the intersection of law and psychology as an area of research and study. Covers topics such as Supreme Court decisions, arrest and trial, juror decision-making, and relevant problems or concerns that arise during investigation, trial and sentencing. (Requirements: Junior standing and prerequisite course or instructor approval.) (Prerequisites: PSF 2551)

records.title: Adv Topics - Forensic Psy
records.subject: PSF
records.description: Offers topics of particular general interest in forensic psychology, criminal justice or criminology when student interest and staffing permit. May be repeated for a maximum of three credits. (Requirement: Junior standing.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Offers topics of particular general interest in forensic psychology, criminal justice or criminology when student interest and staffing permit. May be repeated for a maximum of three credits. (Requirement: Junior standing.) (Prerequisites: PSF 2551)

records.title: Intro to Psychology
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Overviews psychological processes, including both areas in which psychology is a natural science (physiological psychology, sensation and perception, basic learning and cognition) and a social science (motivation, human development, personality, social interaction, psychopathology and psychotherapy). (LA) (SS)

records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces current information and psychological research on aspects of adult development, old age and aging. Examines the intellectual, motivational, psychobiological, social, performance and personality changes that occur in adulthood and old age. (SS)

records.title: Cross-Cult & Ethnic Psy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Examines the relationship between cultural variables and psychological processes from both a psychological and an anthropological perspective. Addresses cultural, international and ethnic issues. (LA) (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the relationship between cultural variables and psychological processes from both a psychological and an anthropological perspective. Addresses cultural, international and ethnic issues. (LA) (SS) (Prerequisites: PSY 1411)

records.subject: PSY
records.description: Surveys the theory, research and applications of psychology pertaining to exercise and sports. Presents current topics and issues relevant to sport psychology. (LA) (SS)

records.title: Group Behavior
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Considers issues of group development, socialization, productivity, decision making and leadership. Emphasizes the application of scientific theory and research to the study of group dynamics in real world group situations. Includes cult and crowd phenomena, social loafing, group therapy, work groups and sports teams. (SS) (LA)

records.title: Psych Learning/Motivation
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Studies the principles of learning and motivation based primarily on nonhuman studies in classical and instrumental conditioning. Focuses on procedures, theories and applications. (LA)
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the principles of learning and motivation based primarily on nonhuman studies in classical and instrumental conditioning. Focuses on procedures, theories and applications. (LA) (Prerequisites: PSY 1411, PSY 2512, PSY 3012)

records.title: Psych Learning/Motivation
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Studies the principles of learning and motivation based primarily on nonhuman studies in classical and instrumental conditioning. Focuses on procedures, theories and applications. (LA)

records.title: Physiological Psychology
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Studies the biological bases of human behavior, including in-depth treatment of nervous system anatomy and physiology, and the biological concepts underlying emotion, motivation, learning and memory. (LA)
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the biological bases of human behavior, including in-depth treatment of nervous system anatomy and physiology, and the biological concepts underlying emotion, motivation, learning and memory. records.title: Psychology of Personality
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Overviews the major theoretical approaches to personality development and research in the field. (LA) (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Overviews the major theoretical approaches to personality development and research in the field. (LA) (SS) (Prerequisites: PSY 1411)

records.title: Memory
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Reviews basic memory processes, theories and research, memory development across the lifespan, and application of principles to everyday life. Balances coverage of both strengths and limitations of memory. Engages students in a series of classic memory experiments and strengthens their own memory through training and testing. (LA)
records.description_with_prereqs: Reviews basic memory processes, theories and research, memory development across the lifespan, and application of principles to everyday life. Balances coverage of both strengths and limitations of memory. Engages students in a series of classic memory experiments and strengthens their own memory through training and testing. (LA) (Prerequisites: BIO 2703, BUS 2703, PSY 2512, PSY 3012)

records.title: Sensation and Perception
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Reviews models, processes and empirical research concerning the modalities of vision, audition, taste, smell and touch/feel. Explores how perception gives rise to our subjective experience and the quality of conscious awareness. (LA)
records.description_with_prereqs: Reviews models, processes and empirical research concerning the modalities of vision, audition, taste, smell and touch/feel. Explores how perception gives rise to our subjective experience and the quality of conscious awareness. (LA) (Prerequisites: PSY 2512)

records.title: Psychology of Leadership
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Examines the research and application of the essential competencies of effective leadership such as managing conflict, facilitating communication and leading groups and teams. (Requirement: Third-year online standing.) (LA) (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the research and application of the essential competencies of effective leadership such as managing conflict, facilitating communication and leading groups and teams. (Requirement: Third-year online standing.) (LA) (SS) (Prerequisites: PSY 1411)

records.title: Psychology of Workplace
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Covers the many ways psychology is applied in organizations to improve performance and quality of work life. Includes employee selection and personnel law, performance management, training, motivation, job attitudes, stress, teamwork, leadership and organizational development. (LA) (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers the many ways psychology is applied in organizations to improve performance and quality of work life. records.title: Intro Child Advocacy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces students to the history of child advocacy, comparative perspectives, legal framework and other interdisciplinary issues pertaining to child maltreatment, response and advocacy. (LA) (SS)

records.title: Comp Animal Cognition
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Explores current topics in animal cognition (from communication to metacognition) in a wide variety of species. Teaches how to appreciate the similarities and difference in cognitive abilities of humans and other animals, and understand why studying the mind of nonhumans provides an important base for cognition in psychology. (LA)

(LA) (Prerequisites: BIO 2801, PSY 3421, PSY 4521)

records.title: Psych Honors Seminar

records.description: Discusses theoretical and empirical research in psychology and related fields in a seminar format. May be repeated for a total of four credits. (Requirement: Acceptance to psychology honors program and department approval.) (LA)

records.description: Analyzes multifactor research designs using analysis of variance and related techniques, including the use of computerized statistical packages and data analysis.
records.description_with_prereqs: Analyzes multifactor research designs using analysis of variance and related techniques, including the use of computerized statistical packages and data analysis. (Prerequisites: PSY 5101)

records.title: Bio Foundations/Behavior
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Emphasizes physiology and pharmacology of the synapse, neuroanatomy, sensory system and complexly motivated behavior. Views normal and abnormal behavior within the biological context and also addresses ethnic, racial, gender and sex-role diversity.
records.description_with_prereqs: Emphasizes physiology and pharmacology of the synapse, neuroanatomy, sensory system and complexly motivated behavior. Views normal and abnormal behavior within the biological context and also addresses ethnic, racial, gender and sex-role diversity.

records.title: Leadership Foundations
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces theories of leadership, research and approaches for developing leaders. Teaches basic leadership theories such as trait, behavioral, contingency, transformational, participative and dyadic leadership. Provides opportunities to link the materials from class to experiences at work through self-discovery and reflection.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces theories of leadership, research and approaches for developing leaders. Teaches basic leadership theories such as trait, behavioral, contingency, transformational, participative and dyadic leadership. Provides opportunities to link the materials from class to experiences at work through self-discovery and reflection.

records.title: Culture & Psychology
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Presents a theoretical basis for understanding the relationship between psychology and cultural studies. Also presents theory and research from cross-cultural psychology, psychological anthropology, cultural psychology, psychological sociology and ethnic studies.
records.description_with_prereqs: Presents a theoretical basis for understanding the relationship between psychology and cultural studies. Also presents theory and research from cross-cultural psychology, psychological anthropology, cultural psychology, psychological sociology and ethnic studies.

records.title: Tests and Measurements
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces psychometric theory, survey of psychological testing and applications to business and industry.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces psychometric theory, survey of psychological testing and applications to business and industry.

records.title: Performance Appraisal
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Studies the application, research and theory in the performance appraisal area. Special emphasis on appraisal skills.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the application, research and theory in the performance appraisal area. Special emphasis on appraisal skills.

records.title: Organizational Psych
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Overviews organizational theories and their relationship to organizational effectiveness. Includes work motivation, organizational attitudes, group processes, leadership and organizational theory.
records.description_with_prereqs: Overviews organizational theories and their relationship to organizational effectiveness. Includes work motivation, organizational attitudes, group processes, leadership and organizational theory.

records.title: Industrial Training
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Examines the methods and applications of training in industry from an integrated systems approach.
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the methods and applications of training in industry from an integrated systems approach.

records.title: Work Motivation
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Focuses on major theoretical issues and applications related to motivation in organizations. (Requirement: Department head approval.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Focuses on major theoretical issues and applications related to motivation in organizations. (Requirement: Department head approval.)

records.title: Psychopathology
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces the classification and diagnosis of the major forms of behavioral and mental pathology and their relationship to models of psychotherapy.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces the classification and diagnosis of the major forms of behavioral and mental pathology and their relationship to models of psychotherapy. (Prerequisites: PSY 5501)

records.title: Objective Assessment
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces current major self-report personality tests with emphasis on administering, scoring and interpreting the MMPI-2/MMPI-A and familiarity with MCMI-III, NEO-PI-R, PAI, 16PF and various checklists. Includes test development issues, ethical standards, test feedback and report-writing skills.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces current major self-report personality tests with emphasis on administering, scoring and interpreting the MMPI-2/MMPI-A and familiarity with MCMI-III, NEO-PI-R, PAI, 16PF and various checklists. Includes test development issues, ethical standards, test feedback and report-writing skills. (Prerequisites: PSY 5501, PSY 5521)

records.title: Clin Skills/Techniques 2
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Provides advanced training in psychotherapeutic techniques and case conceptualization skills necessary for effective psychotherapeutic treatment planning and interventions. Two credits of didactic and one of experiential laboratory.
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides advanced training in psychotherapeutic techniques and case conceptualization skills necessary for effective psychotherapeutic treatment planning and interventions. Two credits of didactic and one of experiential laboratory. (Prerequisites: PSY 5541)

records.title: Dyn/Group Psychotherapy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Studies group psychotherapy from the perspective of research on group dynamics. Considers the history and major types of group therapy, and provides an experiential component.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies group psychotherapy from the perspective of research on group dynamics. Considers the history and major types of group therapy, and provides an experiential component. (Prerequisites: PSY 5501)

records.title: Family Approaches Model
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Includes theory and conceptual foundations of family treatment approaches, and case conceptualization and treatment planning from a family perspective. A lab component incorporates discussion and modeling of techniques, emphasizing the practical application of family intervention procedures.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes theory and conceptual foundations of family treatment approaches, and case conceptualization and treatment planning from a family perspective. A lab component incorporates discussion and modeling of techniques, emphasizing the practical application of family intervention procedures. (Prerequisites: PSY 5542)

records.title: Multicultural Therapy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Provides an applied clinical overview of the major theoretical models of multicultural psychotherapy. Develops skills in using a multicultural orientation to guide the diagnosis, assessment and treatment of psychological disorders.
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides an applied clinical overview of the major theoretical models of multicultural psychotherapy. Develops skills in using a multicultural orientation to guide the diagnosis, assessment and treatment of psychological disorders. (Prerequisites: PSY 5121)

records.title: Seminar/Ethics 2
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Engages in deeper discussion, understanding and implementation of the professional ethics and standards in psychology and one's own professional development. Required for all second-year clinical students.
records.description_with_prereqs: Engages in deeper discussion, understanding and implementation of the professional ethics and standards in psychology and one's own professional development. Required for all second-year clinical students. (Prerequisites: PSY 5591)

records.title: Seminar/Ethics 3
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Continues the discussion, understanding and implementation of the ethical and professional issues within clinical psychology. Emphasizes professional development and involvement, and current topics in professional practice.
records.description_with_prereqs: Continues the discussion, understanding and implementation of the ethical and professional issues within clinical psychology. Emphasizes professional development and involvement, and current topics in professional practice. (Prerequisites: PSY 5592)

records.subject: PSY
records.description: Supervised clinical work in an approved on- or off-campus setting. Placement at sites is determined by the Office of Clinical Training. Experiences will vary among sites to include assessment, intervention, cumulative and supervisory experiences. (Requirement: Clinical director approval and prerequisite course.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Supervised clinical work in an approved on- or off-campus setting. Placement at sites is determined by the Office of Clinical Training. records.title: Clin Forensic Assessment
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Introduces the assessment tools necessary to respond to the needs of the law in criminal responsibility, psychopathy, psychopathology, competency to stand trial and assist counsel, substance abuse, future dangerousness, cognitive abilities and mitigating factors. Also examines the ethical requirements of the psychologist as an expert witness. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or instructor approval.)

Also examines the ethical requirements of the psychologist as an expert witness. (Requirement: Prerequisite course or instructor approval.) (Prerequisites: PSY 6104)

records.title: Multivariate Stats
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Encourages students to use rigorous methodology in the study of organizational issues. Teaches multivariate statistical methods through the use of multiple computer exercises, keeping mathematical details to a minimum. Extensive coverage of both exploratory and confirmatory factor analysis.
records.description_with_prereqs: Encourages students to use rigorous methodology in the study of organizational issues. Teaches multivariate statistical methods through the use of multiple computer exercises, keeping mathematical details to a minimum. Extensive coverage of both exploratory and confirmatory factor analysis.

records.title: Cultural Sem in I/O Psy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Discusses cultural and multicultural issues in industrial/organizational psychology in a research seminar format. May be repeated with instructor's permission.
records.description_with_prereqs: Discusses cultural and multicultural issues in industrial/organizational psychology in a research seminar format. May be repeated with instructor's permission.

records.title: Psychodiagnostics
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Teaches students how to integrate historical, interview, behavioral observations and test data into a clear, accurate and effective psychological report. Weekly test batteries help the student maximally use all available data to address referred questions and cogently communicate results in written format.
records.description_with_prereqs: Teaches students how to integrate historical, interview, behavioral observations and test data into a clear, accurate and effective psychological report. Weekly test batteries help the student maximally use all available data to address referred questions and cogently communicate results in written format. (Prerequisites: PSY 5502, PSY 5521, PSY 5527)

records.title: Marital and Sex Therapy
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Examines the major theoretical approaches to couples' therapy. Provides a survey of human sexuality and the determinants of sexual dysfunction, and assessment and treatment modalities. Includes opportunities for role-play with clinical vignettes. (Requirement: Approval by clinical training director and advanced practicum standing.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the major theoretical approaches to couples' therapy. Provides a survey of human sexuality and the determinants of sexual dysfunction, and assessment and treatment modalities. Includes opportunities for role-play with clinical vignettes. (Requirement: Approval by clinical training director and advanced practicum standing.) (Prerequisites: PSY 5556, PSY 5595)

records.title: Consultation
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Examines the profession and practice of consultation. Models and applications include education and training, and clinical, mental health, behavioral, organizational and program approaches. Reviews common processes, principles and practices of the consulting psychologist.
records.description_with_prereqs: Examines the profession and practice of consultation. Models and applications include education and training, and clinical, mental health, behavioral, organizational and program approaches. Reviews common processes, principles and practices of the consulting psychologist.

records.title: Internship
records.subject: PSY
records.description: Involves 2,000 clock hours of supervised psychological activities in an APA-approved internship setting. records.title: Human Beh Perspective
records.subject: SOC
records.description: Offers an interdisciplinary viewpoint of the many ways in which human beings function as individuals, members of larger groups and members of particular cultures. Explores the disciplines of sociology, psychology and criminology in seeking to understand and explore human behavior. (SS) (Requirement: Must be enrolled in Florida Tech Online.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Offers an interdisciplinary viewpoint of the many ways in which human beings function as individuals, members of larger groups and members of particular cultures. Explores the disciplines of sociology, psychology and criminology in seeking to understand and explore human behavior. (SS) (Requirement: Must be enrolled in Florida Tech Online.)

records.title: American Criminal Justice
records.subject: SOC
records.description: The philosophy and history of the American criminal justice system. Explores interrelationships among system components to include police, courts, institutional corrections, community-based corrections and the juvenile justice system. Contemporary critical issues such as discretion in the administration of criminal justice, race, due process and search and seizure. (SS)
records.description_with_prereqs: The philosophy and history of the American criminal justice system. Explores interrelationships among system components to include police, courts, institutional corrections, community-based corrections and the juvenile justice system. Contemporary critical issues such as discretion in the administration of criminal justice, race, due process and search and seizure. (SS)

records.title: Observational Astronomy
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Combines lecture and observational labs to provide an introduction to the techniques of observational astronomy. Includes celestial coordinate systems, time, apparent stellar motions, constellations, the use of star charts and catalog, and visual CCD photometry.
records.description_with_prereqs: Combines lecture and observational labs to provide an introduction to the techniques of observational astronomy. Includes celestial coordinate systems, time, apparent stellar motions, constellations, the use of star charts and catalog, and visual CCD photometry. (Prerequisites: MTH 1001, MTH 1010, SPS 1010, SPS 1020)

records.title: Observational Astronomy
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Combines lecture and observational labs to provide an introduction to the techniques of observational astronomy. Includes celestial coordinate systems, time, apparent stellar motions, constellations, the use of star charts and catalog, and visual CCD photometry.

records.title: Geophysics
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Introduces the structure, internal constitution, deformation and dynamics of the solid Earth as revealed by surface geophysical manifestations (gravity, magnetic, electrical, seismic). Includes heat flow, electromagnetic induction, tides, the gravitational field and magnetic field.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces the structure, internal constitution, deformation and dynamics of the solid Earth as revealed by surface geophysical manifestations (gravity, magnetic, electrical, seismic). Includes heat flow, electromagnetic induction, tides, the gravitational field and magnetic field. (Prerequisites: MTH 2001, PHY 2002)

records.title: Orbital Mechanics
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Provides the foundations of basic gravitation and orbital theory. Includes coordinate and timekeeping systems, the two-body problem, particle dynamics and motion under inverse square forces, particularly as applied to spacecraft orbit determinations, trajectories, time of flight and maneuvers.
records.description_with_prereqs: Provides the foundations of basic gravitation and orbital theory. Includes coordinate and timekeeping systems, the two-body problem, particle dynamics and motion under inverse square forces, particularly as applied to spacecraft orbit determinations, trajectories, time of flight and maneuvers. (Prerequisites: PHY 3011)

records.title: Astrophysics 2
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Includes galactic coordinates, galactic rotation curve, N-body concepts and the virial theorem, Galactic formation and evolution, external galaxies, galaxy cluster evolution, Hubble's law and the distance scale, large-scale structure, cosmology and the particle physics connection.
records.description_with_prereqs: Includes galactic coordinates, galactic rotation curve, N-body concepts and the virial theorem, Galactic formation and evolution, external galaxies, galaxy cluster evolution, Hubble's law and the distance scale, large-scale structure, cosmology and the particle physics connection. (Prerequisites: SPS 4010)

records.title: Intro Space Plasma Physics
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Introduces the physics of ionized gases beginning with the subjects of single-particle motion, collection of particles, fluid description of plasmas and magnetohydrodynamics. Emphasizes the role of plasmas in solar-terrestrial space physics. Includes heliospheric, magnetospheric and ionospheric topics.
records.description_with_prereqs: Introduces the physics of ionized gases beginning with the subjects of single-particle motion, collection of particles, fluid description of plasmas and magnetohydrodynamics. Emphasizes the role of plasmas in solar-terrestrial space physics. Includes heliospheric, magnetospheric and ionospheric topics. (Prerequisites: PHY 3440, PHY 3440)

records.title: Physics of the Atmosphere
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Studies the behavior of Earth's lower atmosphere, including an introduction to comparative planetology, atmospheric evolution, thermodynamics, dynamics, waves and turbulence, clouds, hurricanes, global circulation and global change.
records.description_with_prereqs: Studies the behavior of Earth's lower atmosphere, including an introduction to comparative planetology, atmospheric evolution, thermodynamics, dynamics, waves and turbulence, clouds, hurricanes, global circulation and global change. (Prerequisites: MTH 2201, PHY 3060)

records.title: Comparative Planetology
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Comprehensively surveys observations from both space-based and Earth-based experimentation, incorporated with the major planetary bodies, asteroids, comets and other small orbitals. Discusses both planetary interiors surface features and atmospheres.
records.description_with_prereqs: Comprehensively surveys observations from both space-based and Earth-based experimentation, incorporated with the major planetary bodies, asteroids, comets and other small orbitals. Discusses both planetary interiors surface features and atmospheres. (Prerequisites: PHY 3060, PHY 3060, SPS 1020)

records.title: Astrobiology
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Covers interstellar and protoplanetary environments, formation and evolution of stars and planets, origin and evolution of life on Earth, terrestrial extremophiles, potentially habitable regions in the solar system, characteristics of extrasolar planets and habitable zones around stars.
records.description_with_prereqs: Covers interstellar and protoplanetary environments, formation and evolution of stars and planets, origin and evolution of life on Earth, terrestrial extremophiles, potentially habitable regions in the solar system, characteristics of extrasolar planets and habitable zones around stars. (Prerequisites: BIO 1020, PHY 3060, SPS 1020)

records.title: Senior Laboratory
records.subject: SPS
records.description: Students conduct experiments in optics, atomic structure, nuclear and solid state physics that are basic to observations in space sciences. (Requirement: Senior standing in space sciences.)
records.description_with_prereqs: Students conduct experiments in optics, atomic structure, nuclear and solid state physics that are basic to observations in space sciences. (Requirement: Senior standing in space sciences.)

records.title: Space Physics 2
records.subject: SPS
records.description: The theoretical background and methods for observing gamma rays, x-rays, high energy electrons and heavy particles, cosmic rays, neutrons and gravitational waves from both spacecraft and Earth. (Requirement: Background knowledge in thermodynamics and statistical mechanics equivalent to PHY 3060.)
records.description_with_prereqs: The theoretical background and methods for observing gamma rays, x-rays, high energy electrons and heavy particles, cosmic rays, neutrons and gravitational waves from both spacecraft and Earth. (Requirement: Background knowledge in thermodynamics and statistical mechanics equivalent to PHY 3060.) (Prerequisites: PHY 5017, SPS 4025, SPS 5020)
